Estrada explores the subject from an interdisciplinary and multiethnic perspective, delving into the pages of local newspapers, diaries and letters, and the personal memories of former and present Plaza residents, in order to examine the spatial and social dimensions of the Plaza over an extended period of time. The author contributes to the growing historiography of Los Angeles by providing a groundbreaking analysis of the original core of the city that covers a long span of time, space, and social relations. He examines the impact of change on the lives of ordinary people in a specific place, and how this change reflects the larger story of the city.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCommunity lifezCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aHuman ecologyzCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aMemoryxSocial aspectszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aPublic spaceszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aSacred spacezCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aWeber, Devra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeber, Devra.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71754140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794627423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794627/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK